a constructed for more. They\nshould stop at all \"Stop\" signs and\nride only on the right side of the\nroad or street. Holding on or\nhitchig to another vehicle is very\ndangerous and they should never\nbe ridden after night without a\nlight on the front and a reflector\nor light on the rear. Never ride\nou t of alleys and driveways, or\nf rom behind parked cars, without\nstopping and looking to see the\nsidewalks or streets are clear of\ntraffic. Obey traffic signals and\nthe orders of traffic officers and at\nno time should youngsters engage\nn trick riding or weave in and out\n0 f traffic on the street or public\nhighways. A bicycle rider should\nhe watchful and alert at all times,\nobey all traffic rules and r\u00e9gula\ntions and at all times be safety\nm inded.\"\n\nr i ni l P\nJF Ta.xVi.TX A liv/I/ XJ \\7J_J\np t- riT[>17\\TTY\n1V| J\\ KIvIjI 1 IVLi\\ U\n_\n\nThough It Has Declined heven\np t p rp\u201en\nPercent in Giams, Fall\nOutlook is Better\n_\nPRODUCTS ARE STEADY\n_\nt\nFarmers were assured today by\ne ureau o Agricu ur\nnomics of a \"fairly well maintain\ned\" consumer buying power and\ndemand for farm products during\nt\nthe last quarter of this year. The\nexplanation is that although busi\n\nness activity has slackened recent\n\nthere is normally a \"lag be\ntween changes in business activity\nand in consumer incomes and de\nImand for farm products.\" The\n\nBureau said that \"the pick-up in\nindustrial activity which usually\nJ\noccurs m the fall may be less than\nj\nwas anticipated by most forecast\nf.\ners a month ago; there may even\nbe some further recession.\" But\nseveral \"bright spots\" also were\ncited in the business outlook, in\neluding \"the settlement of many\n.labor controversies and the sus\ntained farm buying p>ower.\nrecent decline in the general level I\n0 f wholesale prices was attributed\nlargely to a drop of 7 per cent in\nprices of farm products, partlcul\na \u00abY m grain and cotton prices.\nwhole?ale prices in the major for\nei P 1 countries also have weakened\n\u00abace early August. The Bureau\nsaid that the trend of market prie\nes of farm products in the United\nStates slnce mid-August Indicates\na lower eneral level of prices re\ncelved b Y farmers in mid-Septem\nber com Pared with mid-August.\nPrincipal declines have been in\nprices of cotton, grains, and hogs, i\n\nI\nSUNDAY DINNER\nI I\n^^I?flfVlFT\u00bb?_I\n(J\nThe\nr^KAPES \u00abre ia full season, Inelnd\nV\"* native Concords and other\n,1 P* lcin varieties and the California\natln K \u00abrapes such as Thompson seed\nTokays. Malagas and Ribiers.\nApple cranberries and grapefruit\nfruit\u00bb lpin replace the Bummer\nIceberg lettuce is again cheap. To\natoes 0 1 n, \u00b0n\u00bb, peppers and celery are\nreasonable. Potatoes, both white and\nw et ar e low in cost.\nDucklings and lamb are the best\nu ?L J i n meat line though pork ia\na little lower. Both beef and veal\nPricea have risen. Eggs and butter are\nshowing the usual fall increases in\nPrice but arc still reasonable.\nSe asonable foods make up the fol\nlowing menus.\nBy ANN PAGE\nLow Cost Dinner\nPork Chops\nSweet Potato\u00ab\u00ab\nCreamed Cabbaga\nBread and Butter\nApple Tapioca Puddin\nTea or Coffee\nMilk\nMedium Cost Dinner\nM B ak <1 Ham w \u00bbth Appl. Rings\nMashed Potato.. Gr.en B.ans\nR\u00a3? a3 aa< Butter\nFloating Island\nTea or Coffe.\nMilk\nYery Special Dinner\n\u25a0o an<1 Grapefruit Cup\nRoast Duck with Apple and Onion\nStaffing\nro n \u00abd Sweet Potatoes\nBrussels Sprouts\nCombination Salad\nr Bread and Butter\nCoffe. Ice Cream\nCoffee\nR mrm t Studies\nMary Evans, daughter of\nand Mrs w p Evans, of near\nt eswold> has returned to State\nT) eachers College, west Chester,\na wllere \u00abhe has resumed her\nf\u201e U les a JRQior. Miss Evans\na counc tlor of the Women's Co\n2! PatlVe ^^ociation and\np Stant Airman of the College\nresa Board She has been an hon\nor student at the college for her\nnrst two years.\nWafers\nan as\np^N A $275,000\nBUILDING U OF D\nWill Be Located on College\nAvenue and Become the\nChief Center\npians for a $275,000 administra\non building which also would con\ntain dasa rooms for the liberal\narts department of the Cniversity\nDelaware are now being drawn\nby architects. The proposed build\nwd be constructed on the west\nside of the campus between Mitch-!\nell Ha u the, present auditorium\nbuilding, and the Memorial Libr\nary It is to face t he new chem\nistry building, which will be dedi\nca ted on October 16th. Dr. Walter\nHulllhen, president of the univer\ns ity, recently admitted that archi\nbecbs are ab WO rk on plans, but\ngaid that ao f unc js were available\nat p res ent for the building. \"We\nhope to have the administration\nbuilding the next to be construct\ned on the campus,\" he said, \"but\nas we h ave no funds for such a\nbuilding I cannot tell when such a\nbuilding will be built.\" The new\nbuilding would transfer the center\nQ f activities of the men's college\nf rom the present Recitation Hall\nn0 rth of Main street to the cluster\nQ f buildings around the library.\nThis would tend to centralize the\nactivities of the whole university\nadding convenience to the faculties\n311(1 students of the men's college\nand the Women's College,\nbuilding, as projected, will have\ntwo stories generally, with a third\nstory over a portion of it. It would\ncover an area approximately the\nsame as the chemistry building,\nThe first floor would contain the\npresident>s offlce offlces of the\nbusiness manager, and the admin\nistrative staff. The remainder of\nthe building would consist of class\nrooms for the liberal arts school.\nThere is a possibility that classes\nfor both men and women would be\nheld buUding althQUgh of\ncourse, there would be no mixed\nclasses guch a buiIdi WQuld do\nwith the necessity faculty\ny y y\nmembers some time face now be\nclasses of walkimr nearly a\n_ y\nmile from Recitation Hall to the\nAS YET WITHOUT FUNDS\nThe\nWomen s College. With the liber\nbuildiL the chemistry\nal .ff\" 1 t\nU1 e m r ,5.. u m ^j\n\"J. 0 a nCutural\n'Within a few steps of each other,\nbetween classes could\ni \u00abme lost between classes could\nbe greatly reduced. The present\n\u201e\u201ea uk^^oi\n\u00e4Qu llD0r3J \u00e2FLS\n\nbuilding has been in use for near\nAn ar _\ny y\nBROADCAST FOOTBALL. GAME\nAtlantic Reflnl \"S Company\nDelaware eleven who are unable to\nbe present at this season's games\nwill be able to follow the team by\nradio,\npany will sponsor the radio broad\ncasting of eight Delaware games\nover station WDEL, Wilmington,\nIncluded among these are contests\nwith Ursinus on October 2; Rut\ngers on October 9; Lebanon Valley\non October 16; Dickinson on Octo\nber 23; St, John's on October 30;\nPennsylvania Military College on\nNovember 6; Drexel on November\n13 and Washington University on\nNovember 20. The Atlantic Re\nfining Company's 1937 program for\nthe radio broadcasting of intcrcol\ne ^i abe football games is the most\nambitious ever undertaken by a\ncommercial sponsor. Totaling 163\ngames, it embraces 21 complete, or\ncomplete home schedule. In addi\ntion to the University of Delaware,\nthe slate also includes one member\nof the Big Ten\u2014Ohio State\u2014and\nDuke, Georgia, Florida, Syracuse,\nCornell, Holy Cross, Boston Col\nlege. Furman, Virginia, Maryland,\nRichmond, Pennsylvania. Temple,\nVlllanova, Franklin Marshall,\nLafayette, Pittsburgh\nto\nSponsor Radio Program of U. of D.\nFollowers of the University of\nThe Atlantic Refining Com\nAlbright,\nand Carnegie Tech. Also one or\nof Dartmouth, Vlr\nmore games\nginia Military Institute and Uni\nversity of California. The fact\nthat 66 stations and twenty-one\nplay-by-play announcers will be re\nquired to handle the program prop\nerly emphasizes the scope of At\nlantic Refining Company's under\ntaking. Such sponsorship is being\npraised and appreciated by the\nradio public.\nSalisbury Captured Pennant\nJoe Kohlman, 22-year-old right\nhander from Atlantic City, carried\nSalisbury to the Eastern Shore\nLeague championship by pitching\nno-hlt, no-run game against Oen\ntrevllle in the final game of the\nplay-off series.\n0. It was the second time that\nKohlman has allowed no hits and\nno runs.\nhurled against Easton during the\nregular playing season. The game,\nthe fifth of the playoffs, was wit\nnessed by over 2,000 fans.\nThe score was 7 to\nHis first no-hltter was\nWill Release 1,300 Quail\nClarence S. Foster, chief game\nwarden of the Delaware Game and\nFish Commission, directed the re\nlease of approximately 1,300 quail\nin this State last week. The birds\nwere purchased by the commission\nfrom Delaware and Pennsylvania\nbreeders.\nKENT, MD., ROAD WORK\nSenator Brice Thinks It Unlikely\nBy State Before 1941\nIn an address before the Ches\n\"Z\nfavorably of the prospects for any\nimprovements to Kent County,\nMaryland roads before 1941, be-1\ncause the county was formerly re\nceiving $100,000 from the state\ngasoline tax and federal funds,\nwhich was held more than suffici\nent to pay tthe required annual,\namount of $80,000 on outstanding\ncounty road bonds of $1,000,000.\nDuring the year 1937-38, the coun\nty is likely to receive only $48,\n000, which leaves a deficit of $32,\n000, which the Board of County\nCommissioners will be required to\nfurnish from additional tax. levies.\nSenator Brice and members of the\nBoard of County Commissioners\nwere guests of the meeting. The\nprogram was in charge of Robert\nJ- Nicholson.\n\nScreen Test For Miss Delaware\nWhile she didn't land the coveted\ncrown of \"Miss America\" in the\nAtlantic City bathing beauty con-1\ntest, Mias Beatrice (\"Nickey\")\nHarriett, of Harrington, the \"Miss\nDelaware\" selected at the Kent and\nSussex fair, may be able to land\nin the movies, Following the page\nant at Atlantic City, Miss Harriett,\nwho has had some amateur stage\nexperience appeared at one of the\namusement centers on the Steel\nPier, making a pleasing appear\nance. Later she and \"Miss Texas\"\nwere finally selected to visit New\nYork for screen tests.\nEE\nSeptember In\nthe Rain\nU\nThis is the title of a popular song, but rain\nor shine, business people need\nLETTERHEADS\nBILL HEADS\nSTATEMENT'S\nENVELOPES\nCIRCULARS\nBLANK FORMS\nSOCIAL STATIONERY\nOur equipment and selected papers enables us\nto give you good work on any order you may\ngive us. Consult us for modem ideas and\nplans for direct mail pieces, letterheads and\nall forms of printing. Prices are always in\nkeeping with the quality of work. \u2014The Smyr\nna Times, Telephone 10.\nBRIEF ITEMS OF\nTHE PENINSULA\nof\nWe Know in and Around\nFROM OUR EXCHANGES\nLarger Peninsula Towns\nrecently when she was run over by\nan automobile driven by her grand\nfather at their home about 10 miles\nfrom Denton, Md.\nchicken thieves resumed opera\ntion recently in the Milford Neck\nsection, Paris C. Kirby master of\nthe Milford Grange, reporting a\nbig loss in his flock of select poul\ntry.\n\nA two-year-old child was killed\nFrank Taylor meat cutter at the\nstore of Wilbur Hitchens, Seaford,\nis suffering blood poisoning as the\nresult of slashing his hand with a\nknife while cutting meat.\nLieut.-Gov. Edward W.Cooch has\naccepted the invitation of the Vol\nunteer Hose Company of Middle\ntown to attend its 50th anniversary\nbanquet in the fire house Sept em\nher 30th.\nNew shelves have been added at\nthe Middletown school library for\nadditional books. Mrs. Margaret\nP. Ernest who is in charge has de\nveloped a card indext system to\ncheck on each book.\nThe marriage of Miss Pearl Tat\nman and Oien P. Brown, both of\nMilford, has been announced. The\nceremony was performed at Den\nton, Md., September 7 by Rev.\nThomas J. Turkington.\nI\nThe senior English class of the j\nDelaware City High School, under\nthe direction of Donald Harris,\nclass instructor, will issue a school\npaper this year. The name of the\nnew paper is \"The Big Twelve.\"\nJohn F. Herrant, retired employe\nof the Pennsylvania Railroad, Sea\nford, who had been a patient in the\nKent General Hospital, Dover, for\na week, was removed recently to\nthe Delaware Hospital, Wilming\nton.\nLewes high school band, has been\nhonored by the Delaware State Ed\nucation Association as the official\nband to represent the association,\nand will furnish music at the next\ngeneral session of the Teachers' In\nstitute to be held in Wilmington in\nNovember.\n\nMiss Frances J. Buckley, 2914\nWest Fifth street, Wilmington, has\nbeen appointed director of the Mo\ntor Vehicle Department, Dover of\nflee, to succeed Mrs. Clara H. Ray\nmond. Mrs. Raymond has been\nconnected with the department\nsince 1921 and had been director\n\nEight negroes were arrested on\ncharges of playing crap on a public\nhighway recently by Private Leach\nand Corporal Barnes of the state\npolice. They were arrested along\nfor several years.\nthe duPont Boulevard near the in\ntersection of the Townsend High\nway. The eight were fined $5 and\ncosts each by Magistraate Hodgson\nof Townsend.\nDealers from Delaware, New\nYork, Pennsylvania, and Maryland\nwere told last week that the na\ntion's 1937 buckwheat crop will ex\nceed the 1936 yield but probably\nwill be less than the five-year aver\nage. The millers, shippers, and re\nceivers, meeting at Elmira. N. Y.,\nin annual session, estimated the\nseason's crop at approximately 7,\n225,000 bushels.\nAll operations of a dredging na\nture in the Chesapeake and Dela\nware Canal are confined to the\nvicinity of Summit Bridge and the\nwhere the finishing\n\"deep cut\"\ntouches are being put on the task\nof converting the waterway from a\n112-foot canal to a 27-foot depth\nand a 250-foot width ship canal,\nft is estimated that the project is\nabout 98 per cent completed.\nThe 30th series of shares of the\nDelaware City Building and Loan\nAssociation mature with the Sep\ntember payment and arrangements\nare now being made by Harry C.\nPrice, treasurer, to pay off share\nholders as soon as possible after all\nthe payments are received. The\nseries is one of the larger ones to\nmature, having a total of 97 shares\nworth $19,400 agaainst which $7,\n400 has been borrowed.\n\nHigh school Latin helps one if\nhe retains some scholarly vestiges\nafter he leaves school.","height":"21072","width":"14652"}}
